@page "/about"

<PageTitle>About TheDiscDb</PageTitle>
<HeadContent>
    <meta name="description" content="TheDiscDb is a community-built database of Blu-ray, 4K UHD, and DVD disc structures. Find out exactly which MakeMKV playlist is the movie — no guessing required." />
    <link rel="canonical" href="https://thediscdb.com/about" />
</HeadContent>

<TheDiscDb.Client.Controls.Breadcrumb PrimaryText="About" Items='[("Home", "/")]' />

<div class="page-header">
    <h1>About <span class="page-header__accent">TheDiscDb</span></h1>
    <div class="page-header__desc">
        A community-built database that maps every Blu-ray, 4K UHD, and DVD playlist to its actual
        content — so you always know which file is the movie.
    </div>
</div>

<div class="contribute-layout about-page">

    <section class="info-grid">
        <article class="info-card">
            <h2>The disc playlist problem</h2>
            <p>
                When you open a Blu-ray in <a href="https://makemkv.com" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">MakeMKV</a>,
                you see dozens of unnamed files: <code>00003.mpls</code>, <code>00011.mpls</code>,
                <code>00029.mpls</code>… There is no label telling you which one is the movie. Disc publishers use
                complex playlist schemes for region variants, seamless branching, and sometimes intentionally to
                frustrate automated ripping.
            </p>
        </article>

        <article class="info-card">
            <h2>What TheDiscDb does</h2>
            <p>
                Contributors who have already ripped a disc share exactly what they found — which file is the main
                feature, which are extras, and what the suggested output filename is. When you look up your release
                you get the full disc map and can rip the right file the first time, every time.
            </p>
        </article>
    </section>

    <section class="about-stats-bar">
        <div class="about-stats-item">
            <span class="about-stats-number">@(stats?.Movies.ToString("N0") ?? "—")</span>
            <span class="about-stats-label">Movies</span>
        </div>
        <div class="about-stats-divider" aria-hidden="true"></div>
        <div class="about-stats-item">
            <span class="about-stats-number">@(stats?.Series.ToString("N0") ?? "—")</span>
            <span class="about-stats-label">Series</span>
        </div>
        <div class="about-stats-divider" aria-hidden="true"></div>
        <div class="about-stats-item">
            <span class="about-stats-number">@(stats?.Boxsets.ToString("N0") ?? "—")</span>
            <span class="about-stats-label">Box Sets</span>
        </div>
        <div class="about-stats-divider" aria-hidden="true"></div>
        <div class="about-stats-item">
            <span class="about-stats-number">@(stats?.Discs.ToString("N0") ?? "—")</span>
            <span class="about-stats-label">Discs</span>
        </div>
        <div class="about-stats-divider" aria-hidden="true"></div>
        <div class="about-stats-item">
            <span class="about-stats-number">@(stats?.Contributors.ToString("N0") ?? "—")</span>
            <span class="about-stats-label">Contributors</span>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="info-card about-example-card">
        <h2>See it in action</h2>
        <p>
            Here is what the database shows for the
            <a href="/movie/heat-1995/releases/heat-blu-ray-2009/discs/blu-ray-2009">Heat (1995) Blu-ray</a>.
            Every playlist is already identified — no guessing required:
        </p>
        <div class="about-example-table-wrapper">
            <table class="about-example-table">
                <thead>
                    <tr>
                        <th>Source File</th>
                        <th>Description</th>
                        <th>Type</th>
                        <th>Suggested Filename</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code>00003.mpls</code></td>
                        <td>Heat (1995)</td>
                        <td><span class="type-badge type-main">Main Movie</span></td>
                        <td><code>Heat (1995) [1080p].mkv</code></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code>00011.mpls</code></td>
                        <td>The Making of HEAT</td>
                        <td><span class="type-badge type-extra">Featurette</span></td>
                        <td><code>The Making of HEAT.mkv</code></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><code>00029.mpls</code></td>
                        <td>Trailers</td>
                        <td><span class="type-badge type-trailer">Trailer</span></td>
                        <td><code>Trailers.mkv</code></td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="info-card contribute-cta-card">
        <h2>Want to contribute?</h2>
        <p>
            Scan your disc with MakeMKV, upload the log, and label the titles. When you share the layout
            of your discs with the community — everyone benefits. Your name is credited on every release
            you contribute.
        </p>
        <div class="cta-row">
            <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/contribute">Start contributing</a>
            <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/help/contributing">How it works</a>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="info-grid">
        <article class="info-card">
            <h2>Suggest an edit</h2>
            <p>
                Spotted incorrect metadata? Any signed-in user can click the pencil icon on any release,
                disc, or chapter page and submit a correction for review.
            </p>
            <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/help/suggested-edits">Learn about suggested edits</a>
        </article>

        <article class="info-card">
            <h2>Browse the database</h2>
            <p>
                Search by title, or browse by genre, director, or actor. Over 1,300 movies and 150 series
                with full disc structures are waiting.
            </p>
            <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="/">Browse movies</a>
        </article>
    </section>

    <section class="info-card contact-card">
        <h2>Contact us</h2>
        <p>
            Need help, need to correct metadata, or want to partner? Email us at
            <a href="mailto:web@thediscdb.com">web@thediscdb.com</a> or <a href="https://github.com/TheDiscDb/web/discussions" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">open a discussion on GitHub</a>.
        </p>
        <div class="cta-row">
            <a class="btn btn-secondary" href="mailto:web@thediscdb.com">Email support</a>
            <a class="btn btn-primary" href="https://github.com/orgs/TheDiscDb/discussions" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
                Join the discussion
            </a>
        </div>
    </section>
</div>